 </disp-formula>where ellipses (…) were used to represent higher-order derivatives. Extending the manifold over the additional dimensions extends the integration volume element. By extending the regional manifold in Eq. 
 <xref rid="fd4" ref-type="disp-formula">(4)</xref> with the bridge manifold of Eq. 
 <xref rid="fd5" ref-type="disp-formula">(5)</xref>, we get (
 <xref rid="bib5" ref-type="bibr">Grignani et al., 2017</xref>):
 <disp-formula id="fd6">
  <label>(6)</label>
  <math id="M16" display="block" altimg="si16.svg" alttext="Equation 6.">
   <mrow>
    <msubsup>
     <mi>S</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mi>b</mi>
      <mi>r</mi>
      <mi>i</mi>
      <mi>d</mi>
      <mi>g</mi>
      <mi>e</mi>
